                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The 21-SI series Delcotron Integral Charging System is a high output alternator (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0801701">Figure 1</hotlnk>) with integral diode rectifier and voltage
                        regulator, producing DC current for battery electrical systems.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0801701" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0801701" filename="../figg08/G0801701.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>21-SI Alternator</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. SLIP RING END (SRE) HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. STATOR</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. DRIVE END (DE) FRAME</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. ADJUSTMENT LUG</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. FAN</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. PULLEY</callout1>
                            <callout1>7. MOUNTING LUGS</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>International vehicles built before March 15, 1992, with a 21-SI alternator will have a one
                        (1) wire alternator. Those built after March 15, 1992, will have a two (2) wire type.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The solid state, integrated circuit voltage regulator built into the 21-SI alternator limits
                        system voltage by switching the ground circuit for the rotor field on and off. When the ground
                        circuit is on, field current passes from a diode trio through the rotor via brushes and slip
                        rings on the rotor shaft. The nominal regulated output voltage is 14.2 volts for all 21-SI
                        output ranges.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Both the one-wire and two-wire types require that the alternator output (BAT) terminal be
                        connected to the battery positive terminal and that a ground path be provided between the
                        alternator housing and the battery negative terminal. The two-wire alternator will have a lead
                        from the "I" terminal to the accessory side of the ignition switch (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0801702">Figure 2</hotlnk>). The two-wire alternator will function with or
                        without the ignition turn-on circuit. The turn-on circuit is used to lower the alternator
                        turn-on speed. An "R" terminal connection is optional and does not affect the alternator
                        operation. A threaded grounding connection is also available (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0801703">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0801702" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0801702" filename="../figg08/G0801702.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Basic Two-Wire System</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. ALTERNATOR</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. AMMETER (IF USED)</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. BATTERY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. VOLTMETER (IF USED)</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. IGNITION SWITCH</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. SYSTEM LOAD</callout1>
                            <callout1>7. OUTPUT TERMINAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>8. RESISTOR WIRE</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <figure id="f0801703" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0801703" filename="../figg08/G0801703.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>21-SI Electrical Terminals</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. RELAY "R" TERMINAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. OUTPUT "BAT" TERMINAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. THREADED GROUND TERMINAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. "D" SHAPED TEST HOLE</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. "I" TERMINAL</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The "I" terminal is located clockwise from the BAT terminal and is identified by an I molded
                        into the casting. The "I" terminal is connected internally to the field circuit and externally
                        through a resistor wire to the accessory connector on the ignition switch.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
